      <hedline>
        <hl1>Quotas in Florida</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Stuart Shelby letter says Florida's use of quotas in its college admissions program expresses contempt for achievement and fosters stereotype that minority students are unable to compete academically with whites (Sept 15 Op-Ed)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Gov. Jeb Bush states that 85 percent of the students in Florida's lowest-performing secondary schools are African-American, Hispanic or members of other minority groups (''Better Than Affirmative,'' Op-Ed, Sept. 15).</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Gov. Jeb Bush states that 85 percent of the students in Florida's lowest-performing secondary schools are African-American, Hispanic or members of other minority groups (''Better Than Affirmative,'' Op-Ed, Sept. 15).</p>
        <p>Having a diverse student body is a compelling goal. The use of quotas, however, to guarantee the admission to state universities of every Florida student who graduates in the top 20 percent of his or her high school class in the lowest-performing secondary schools unfairly denies admission to candidates with higher academic achievement who fail to meet the quota for their schools.</p>
        <p>A university should be a meritocracy. The Florida admissions program expresses contempt for achievement and promotes racism by fostering stereotypes that certain minority students are unable to compete academically with whites.</p>
        <p>STUART SHELBY  Santa Monica, Calif., Sept. 16, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
